snippet.textDisplay: Nintendo was working with Sony to develop an optical disc based add-on for the SNES...which became the PlayStation when the collaboration broke down.  Fast forward to today, Microsoft has the best hardware, but can't seem to get any great exclusive titles and Nintendo has a deep chest of 1st party exclusives but an underpowered handheld they call a console.  They have been building a better working relationship with one another, and neither has really ever seen the other as competition in the gaming space.  They're working to bring Xbox Live, and now possibly game pass, to the Switch.  I think it's a distinct possibility, albeit wild speculation, that their next gen consoles could be interconnected.  Think Vita and PS3, with cross-saves, etc, except that people will actually want to buy the handheld.  I am imagining a handheld similar to the Switch, developed primarily by Nintendo and a powerful home console developed primarily by Microsoft with an ecosystem that runs on both, also developed primarily  by Microsoft.  This would fit their business model of selling services, not hardware, and honestly would be an incredible move for both companies.

They have been building a better working relationship with one another, and neither has really ever seen the other as competition in the gaming space.  They're working to bring Xbox Live, and now possibly game pass, to the Switch.  I think it's a distinct possibility, albeit wild speculation, that their next gen consoles could be interconnected. This would fit their business model of selling services, not hardware, and honestly would be an incredible move for both companies.
